45: /**
46:  * RecordBatch implementation for magic 2 and above. The schema is given below:
47:  *
48:  * RecordBatch =>
49:  *  BaseOffset => Int64
50:  *  Length => Int32
51:  *  PartitionLeaderEpoch => Int32
52:  *  Magic => Int8
53:  *  CRC => Uint32
54:  *  Attributes => Int16
55:  *  LastOffsetDelta => Int32 // also serves as LastSequenceDelta
56:  *  BaseTimestamp => Int64
57:  *  MaxTimestamp => Int64
58:  *  ProducerId => Int64
59:  *  ProducerEpoch => Int16
60:  *  BaseSequence => Int32
61:  *  RecordsCount => Int32
62:  *  Records => [Record]
63:  *
64:  * Note that when compression is enabled (see attributes below), the compressed record data is serialized
65:  * directly following the count of the number of records.
66:  *
67:  * The CRC covers the data from the attributes to the end of the batch (i.e. all the bytes that follow the CRC). It is
68:  * located after the magic byte, which means that clients must parse the magic byte before deciding how to interpret
69:  * the bytes between the batch length and the magic byte. The partition leader epoch field is not included in the CRC
70:  * computation to avoid the need to recompute the CRC when this field is assigned for every batch that is received by
71:  * the broker. The CRC-32C (Castagnoli) polynomial is used for the computation.
72:  *
73:  * On Compaction: Unlike the older message formats, magic v2 and above preserves the first and last offset/sequence
74:  * numbers from the original batch when the log is cleaned. This is required in order to be able to restore the
75:  * producer's state when the log is reloaded. If we did not retain the last sequence number, then following
76:  * a partition leader failure, once the new leader has rebuilt the producer state from the log, the next sequence
77:  * expected number would no longer be in sync with what was written by the client. This would cause an
78:  * unexpected OutOfOrderSequence error, which is typically fatal. The base sequence number must be preserved for
79:  * duplicate checking: the broker checks incoming Produce requests for duplicates by verifying that the first and
80:  * last sequence numbers of the incoming batch match the last from that producer.
81:  *
82:  * Note that if all of the records in a batch are removed during compaction, the broker may still retain an empty
83:  * batch header in order to preserve the producer sequence information as described above. These empty batches
84:  * are retained only until either a new sequence number is written by the corresponding producer or the producerId
85:  * is expired from lack of activity.
86:  *
87:  * There is no similar need to preserve the timestamp from the original batch after compaction. The BaseTimestamp
88:  * field therefore reflects the timestamp of the first record in the batch in most cases. If the batch is empty, the
89:  * BaseTimestamp will be set to -1 (NO_TIMESTAMP). If the delete horizon flag is set to 1, the BaseTimestamp
90:  * will be set to the time at which tombstone records and aborted transaction markers in the batch should be removed.
91:  *
92:  * Similarly, the MaxTimestamp field reflects the maximum timestamp of the current records if the timestamp type
93:  * is CREATE_TIME. For LOG_APPEND_TIME, on the other hand, the MaxTimestamp field reflects the timestamp set
94:  * by the broker and is preserved after compaction. Additionally, the MaxTimestamp of an empty batch always retains
95:  * the previous value prior to becoming empty.
96:  *
97:  * The current attributes are given below:
98:  *
99:  *  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
100:  *  | Unused (7-15) | Delete Horizon Flag (6) | Control (5) | Transactional (4) | Timestamp Type (3) | Compression Type (0-2) |
101:  *  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
102:  */
103: public class DefaultRecordBatch extends AbstractRecordBatch implements MutableRecordBatch {
104:     static final int BASE_OFFSET_OFFSET = 0;
105:     static final int BASE_OFFSET_LENGTH = 8;
106:     static final int LENGTH_OFFSET = BASE_OFFSET_OFFSET + BASE_OFFSET_LENGTH;
107:     static final int LENGTH_LENGTH = 4;
108:     static final int PARTITION_LEADER_EPOCH_OFFSET = LENGTH_OFFSET + LENGTH_LENGTH;
109:     static final int PARTITION_LEADER_EPOCH_LENGTH = 4;
110:     static final int MAGIC_OFFSET = PARTITION_LEADER_EPOCH_OFFSET + PARTITION_LEADER_EPOCH_LENGTH;
111:     static final int MAGIC_LENGTH = 1;
112:     public static final int CRC_OFFSET = MAGIC_OFFSET + MAGIC_LENGTH;
113:     static final int CRC_LENGTH = 4;
114:     static final int ATTRIBUTES_OFFSET = CRC_OFFSET + CRC_LENGTH;
115:     static final int ATTRIBUTE_LENGTH = 2;
116:     public static final int LAST_OFFSET_DELTA_OFFSET = ATTRIBUTES_OFFSET + ATTRIBUTE_LENGTH;
117:     static final int LAST_OFFSET_DELTA_LENGTH = 4;
118:     static final int BASE_TIMESTAMP_OFFSET = LAST_OFFSET_DELTA_OFFSET + LAST_OFFSET_DELTA_LENGTH;
